 Our results suggest that up to 30% of the variability occurring in the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation is likely to be chaotic i.e. linked to processes that cannot directly be predicted from the atmospheric forcing alone (e.g. ocean mesoscale eddies).</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The model described above will be the key tool to improve our understanding of the processes governing the variability of the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation. All the data of our model simulations are available on the JASMIN data server and therefore available to scientists from other research institutions.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>D9180FE6-94D7-4267-8828-564D8EAD2717</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>Performance of a new, long global ocean simulation at 1/12&amp;deg; (NEMO ocean model in ORCA12 configuration). The simulation covers the period from 1958 to 2014.</gtr:description><gtr:id>38C7DBD8-83D9-4B31-9C5F-91B87606DDEE</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This simulation will provide with a unique opportunity to improve our understanding of the mechanisms behind the variability of the North Atlantic Meridional Overturning circulation.</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>false</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>Eddy-resolving simulation</gtr:title><gtr:type>Improvements to research infrastructure</gtr:type></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/4C1AEA7B-F098-4239-AB7D-C79E710A8BDC"><gtr:id>4C1AEA7B-F098-4239-AB7D-C79E710A8BDC</gtr:id><gtr:title>Drivers of exceptionally cold North Atlantic Ocean temperatures and their link to the 2015 European heat